TI  - Efficacy and tolerance of mild induced hypothermia after out-of-hospital cardiac arrest using an endovascular cooling system
T2  - CRITICAL CARE
AB  - Background: To assess the efficacy, the tolerance and the ability of mild therapeutic hypothermia using an endovascular cooling system to reach and to maintain a target temperature of 33 degrees C after cardiac arrest.
   Methods: Case series in the medical-surgical intensive care unit ( ICU) of an urban university hospital. 40 patients admitted to the ICU after an out-of-hospital cardiac arrest underwent mild induced hypothermia ( MIH). Core temperature was monitored continuously for 5 days using a Foley catheter equipped with a temperature sensor. Any equipment malfunction was noted and all adverse events attributable to MIH were collected. The neurological status was evaluated daily using Pittsburgh cerebral performance category ( CPC). The mechanism of cardiac arrest, the Simplified Acute Physiologic Score ( SAPS) II on admission, standard biological variables, and time lags characterizing the duration of cerebral hypoperfusion were recorded. Nosocomial infections were collected during and after MIH until day 28.
   Results: Six patients ( 15%) died during hypothermia. Among the 34 patients who completed the period of MIH, hypothermia was maintained steady in 31 patients ( 91%). Post re-warming "rebound hyperthermia" determined as temperature >= 38.5 degrees C was observed in 25 patients ( 74%) during the first 24 hours which followed the cessation of MIH. Infectious complications were observed in 18 patients ( 45%), but no patient developed severe sepsis or septic shock. Biological changes during MIH principally resulted in hypokaliemia < 3.5 mmol/L ( 75%).
   Conclusion: The intravascular cooling system is effective, safe and allows reaching a target temperature fairly rapidly and steadily over a period of 36h.
