AB  - Background: Uterine leiomyomas are the most common benign tumours affecting women of reproductive age. Complications of leiomyomas include torsion, red degeneration, carcinomatous change and rarely-perforation and/or hemorrhage. This case report highlights the atypical presentation of spontaneous haemorrhage from a uterine fibroid that clinicians should consider as a differential diagnosis for haemoperitoneum. It adds to the existing literature in discussing the investigations and management of this rare fibroid complication.
   Case Description: We report a case of an atypical presentation of spontaneous hemorrhage from a uterine fibroid with no precipitating factors in a stable patient who did not require blood transfusion. A 28-year-old nulliparous woman presented with 2-day history of abdominal pain and an outpatient pelvic ultrasound (US) suggesting hemoperitoneum. She was hemodynamically stable. Her abdomen was soft, generally tender across the lower abdomen with some voluntary guarding. Her initial haemoglobin (Hb) was 114 g/L. Serial Hb showed a drop to 86 g/L after 12 hours. She had an urgent US which demonstrated a large vascular complex pelvic mass of uncertain etiology with a large amount of hemoperitoneum (>430 mL). A computed tomography (CT) and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of abdomen/pelvis showed extensive hemoperitoneum, and a large 86x94 mm exophytic homogenously enhancing mass lesion arising from the posterior uterus with no source of active bleeding seen. She underwent diagnostic laparoscopy. A large pedunculated fibroid arising from right anterior cornua was found with similar to 1 L hemoperitoneum. An active bleeding point was identified arising from this fibroid. As it was difficult to control bleeding and in view of findings laparotomy was performed. The fibroid pedicle was secured with LigaSure, and the fibroid detached. The patient remained well and was discharged the next day with Hb 89 g/L with no blood transfusion required. At her 6-week post operative follow-up the incision was healed and she was well.
   Conclusions: Hemorrhage secondary to a uterine fibroid is a rare complication of uterine fibroids that clinicians must consider. Initial rapid imaging can be used to narrow down the diagnosis. Prompt resuscitation, definitive surgical management in a multi-disciplinary team approach will aid in management and improve outcomes.
